12:27.540 --> 12:32.440
Norman Spinrad's 1979 science fiction novel, A World Between, signaled a change in his fiction.

12:32.440 --> 12:37.940
Spinrad's early work usually contain either subtle or overt criticism of various aspects of society.

12:38.440 --> 12:42.940
Bugjack Barron, the men in the jungle, and agent of chaos are good examples of this type.

12:43.380 --> 12:46.690
A World Between is also a socially oriented novel, but there's a different...

12:58.480 --> 13:00.660
...front element in it. Spinrad explains.

13:01.840 --> 13:14.480
I would say in general that up until, I guess, The World Between really, a lot of my stuff was kind of critical of this,

13:15.060 --> 13:19.660
of critical of existing societies, critical of various things that were going on.

13:20.280 --> 13:25.220
A World Between is meant as a utopian novel, really, in any kind of way.

13:25.220 --> 13:27.320
And it's a prescriptive kind of book.

13:28.080 --> 13:32.820
It's more of a... instead of presenting critical images of other things,

13:33.260 --> 13:38.120
the idea is to create a more positive image of a more positive kind of future.

13:38.320 --> 13:40.860
I think if you spend enough time criticizing what exists,

13:43.240 --> 13:50.460
at some point you have some kind of moral obligation to present something more positive and replace...

13:50.980 --> 13:53.000
...what you find negative.

13:57.780 --> 14:00.500
The setting for the novel is a fit one for a utopia.

14:01.000 --> 14:06.880
It takes place on the planet Pacifica, a beautiful world of blue ocean and lush green islands that's been colonized by humans.

14:07.680 --> 14:10.680
Inhabitants of Pacifica live private lives in their isolated islands.

14:11.260 --> 14:14.760
There are no large urban centers to cause pollution over population or poverty.

14:14.760 --> 14:20.200
Even though they are physically isolated, the Pacificans remain in close electronic contact with one another.

14:20.680 --> 14:26.440
They govern themselves, in fact, with a tight media web that allows them to vote immediately on any issue of importance.

14:26.940 --> 14:30.540
But into this idyllic world comes two opposed political forces from Earth,

14:30.700 --> 14:33.120
bent on the ideological conquest of Pacifica.

14:33.380 --> 14:36.040
One force is the Institute for Transcendental Science,

14:36.480 --> 14:40.380
a powerful organization whose goal is galactic unity under their control.

14:40.380 --> 14:44.140
They are extreme, and Spinrad says they have two basic flaws.

14:45.420 --> 14:50.520
One is the unexamined, subtle male shoveness bias of their culture.

14:51.720 --> 15:01.860
And the other one is the ultimate conviction that what they are doing is the absolute most important thing in the universe,

15:02.080 --> 15:08.960
and that therefore they are morally entitled to run over other people's cultures.

15:08.960 --> 15:20.500
And then, and then this is our, absoluteism I guess would be the, even the kind of theocratic absoluteism would be their, would be their flaws.

15:21.020 --> 15:25.220
The other force is the Femocrats, a militant women's liberation group that is also an extreme.

15:25.800 --> 15:30.600
The struggle of these two groups for control of planets all across the galaxy is called the Pink and Blue War.

15:30.920 --> 15:37.300
It's clearly a male-female conflict, and so far every planet the two sides have approached has ended up on one side or the other.

15:37.300 --> 15:41.700
But Pacifica is different. Spinrad's utopia is a stable and intelligent one.

15:42.220 --> 15:46.640
The Pacificans reject both extremes and even change the minds of a few of the combatants.

15:46.820 --> 15:52.200
We asked Spinrad about reactions to the book. How did women for instance respond to the Femocratic women's livers?

15:53.500 --> 16:01.700
The strange thing about the reaction to that book has been that a certain number of men have, you know,

16:01.700 --> 16:08.760
reacted in a kind of male, male liberal guilt, male feminist kind of reaction against that.

16:09.360 --> 16:14.400
But at most part women have liked the book. Women have identified with it more than men.

16:15.880 --> 16:19.580
And actually I even got one or two good reviews in feminist places.

16:20.340 --> 16:24.200
I think that's not quite what I expected, but that seems to be the way it happened.

16:24.380 --> 16:29.000
I have not gotten a heavy feminist flag from that a little bit, but not much.

16:29.000 --> 16:34.600
Not much, because I think women who are involved in feminism or have been or know women who are,

16:35.400 --> 16:42.240
can recognize a certain aspect of the feminist movement in the Femocrats.

16:42.340 --> 16:46.980
Whereas men who are trying to show how liberator they are would not dream of admitting such a thing.

16:47.640 --> 16:52.440
A world between. A different sort of book for Norman Spinrad, and we'll have more on him tomorrow.

